properties.Name: Nantahala Mountains
properties.description:
Dick’s Creek Gap to Fontana Dam March 2006
Our initial intention in planning this hike was to leave a car at Fontana Dam, get a shuttle ride to Dicks Creek Gap, and backpack north back to our car. We hoped to do the hike in seven days, which was the exact amount of time I had available during spring break. As the time of the trip approached, we decided to day-hike the section instead, for two reasons – both related to the short time frame. One was that Tatiana had developed a wrist injury in a minor fall, and we were concerned about her ability to complete the hike. The other was that the forecast called for cold temperatures and snow, and we were concerned that a large amount of snow could slow our progress to the point that we would not complete the hike in time. So we planned a day-hike itinerary with more miles per day, camping each night at National Forest campgrounds accessible by car.

properties.Name: Georgia: Dicks Creek Gap to Amicalola Falls
properties.description:
Dick’s Creek Gap to Amicalola Falls This hike was a backpacking trip during spring break. We had two weeks off, and spent the first week touring historic sites and natural areas in Tennessee, Alabama, and Georgia. Then we drove to Amicalola Falls State Park, which serves as the gateway to the trail, and were driven by a local guy with a truck up to Dicks Creek Gap, on US 76.

properties.Name: Smokies and the Roan Highlands
properties.description:
Smokies and the Roan Highlands
In June of 2007 I hiked my final section of the trail, from Fontana Dam at the southeastern end of the Smoky Mountains (http://www.nps.gov/grsm) to Roan Mountain. (http://friendsofroanmtn.org/default.htm) After Tatiana and I hiked Roan Mountain two years earlier, we decided it would be a fitting spot for finishing the trail. I started hiking at Fontana Dam and finished at Roan Mountain.

properties.Name: Mt Rogers Higlands
properties.description:
Roan Mountain highlands and Mt. Rogers
In June of 2005 we had some time for a trip in June. One of my goals in section hiking was to hike various sections of the trail during a season when they might be best appreciated. We knew that in the Roan Mountain and Mt. Rogers areas there were natural gardens of rhododendrons that would be in boom around mid-June, so we decided to head that direction. The trip was organized around the idea of base camping for several days in one place while we day-hiked sections of the AT. The overall route was from Roan Mountain to the Settler's Museum, just south of the first crossing of I-81.

properties.Name: Central Virginia
properties.description:
We hiked this section during two separate trips. In April 2006 we started a backpacking trip near Pearisburg, hoping to hike south to I-81. The trip was cut short half way through when I got sick. In April 2007 we hiked the unfinished section around Burkes Garden, a beautiful pastoral valley surrounded by mountains known as "God's thumbprint". Then we also hiked from Pearisburg north to beyond Roanoke, where the trail joins the Blue Ridge Parkway for the first time. The weather was sunny and summer-like for the first 3 days, then turned rapidly colder for the rest of the trip. In addition to Burkes Garden, highlights of this trip included Dragon's Tooth and McAfee Knob

properties.Name: Virginia and the Mid-Atlantic
properties.description:
I hiked most of this section as day hikes, with a few weekend backpacking trips here and there. The section starts along the Blue Ridge Parkway near Roanoke, continues through Shenandoah and norther Virginia, passes through Harpers Ferry and Maryland, then across the rocky ridges of Pennsylvania. It continues across Delaware Water Gap through New Jersey to Harriman State Park in NY

properties.Name: Maine
properties.description:
I started this section near Gorham, NH, after riding on a bus from Washington to DC, with stops in New York City and Boston. The first few days were rainy, but after that I was rewarded with spectacular weather. Shelters along the trail were still welcomed because of frequent late afternoon/evening thunderstorms. I hiked through the very rugged Mahoosic range, the Bigelows and Saddleback ranges, and then into the lake country and the 100 mile wilderness. One highlight was Moxie Bald, where a picked blueberries atop the open summitt. At the end of the route I climbed Katahdin.

properties.Name: Vermont and New Hampshire
properties.description:
For this section, I took two weeks to hike from near Manchester, Vermont through most of the White Mountains in New Hampshire. I started in the Green Mountains, climbing the prominent peaks of Bromley and Killington. North of Killington the trail turns east and follows a lower ridge to the NH border, then becomes increasingly rocky and rugged as it approaches the Whites. Highlights in the White Mountains included the Pemigasasett Wilderness, the Presidential Range, and the Carter-Moriah Range. I stayed at a Hut in Carter Notch for a night towards the end of the trip. I ended at US route 2, along the Androscoggin River, east of Gorham.
